ve habit of trying to force spiritual discussions on others, now th=\r\nankfully I am relatively cured. On our part, what we can do is not to fall =\r\nin the trap of thinking that because we are doing some sadhana, or have som=\r\ne interest in these things therefore we are anyway better. Not at all. Ther=\r\ne is beauty in diversity. I have seen rank atheists who have more detachmen=\r\nt and equanimity than many believers. If you want to discuss spirituality, =\r\nfind a group of friends with similar inclination and do so. But never try t=\r\no force it on an unwilling individual. Whenever force is applied, it invari=\r\nable leads to a unpredictable and at times unpleasant reaction at some late=\r\nr\n date. \n\nOne of the people whom I consider as one of my gurus, had told m=\r\ne once, &quot;Duniya banane wala duniya chalana bhi janta hai&quot; (One who made the=\r\n world also knows how to run the world). Now I believe that statement is ba=\r\nng on. Feel no pressure. Everything is in safe hands!\n\n&lt;&lt; 5. Why =C3=82 did=\r\n Gautam Buddha left his wife and his child and even then achieved the statu=\r\ns of God?&gt;&gt;\n\nIn my view, we use the term God too loosely. There are Mahatma=\r\ns, great Mahatmas, fantastic spiritual beings, and then there is God. Buddh=\r\na was a fantastic and super-duper spiritual being.\n\nNow coming to your ques=\r\ntion, there is no fixed rule of how and what can lead a man to liberation o=\r\nr higher states of spirituality. Frankly, there is no path which *guarantee=\r\ns* liberation. All paths have the potential, but realization is an individu=\r\nal&#39;s journey, and each such journey will not be a mirror of anyone else&#39;s j=\r\nourney. Broadly there may be similarities, but nuances will differ. For som=\r\ne it is necessary to leave their wife and children to be spiritual, for oth=\r\ners they may not need to do so. \n\nInfact, the aim of sadhana is to prepare =\r\nyourself. If and when you experience and realize God, it is going be God&#39;s =\r\nsweet will. Sadhana does not guarantee realization, but without sadhana it =\r\nis nearly impossibly, for you are simply not prepared enough to experience.=\r\n \n\n&lt;&lt;3. I was reading =C3=82 a newspaper that people after having darshan o=\r\nf Mata Vaishno Devi, Kedarnaath, etc =C3=82 , while returning, met with acc=\r\nident and died. Why does this happen? People have just come from a such a w=\r\nonderful darshan then why tragedy strikes them.&gt;&gt; \n\nThe idea of trying to f=\r\norce a cause effect relation to everything is an inherent tendency of the m=\r\nind. It is not necessarily how things are. Neither is it useful.\n\nIf a man =\r\nwants to only experience God, then every life-experience, apparently good o=\r\nr apparently bad, is only going to take your forward towards the goal if yo=\r\nu keep your aim fixed. No wonder Lord Krishna stresses so much on detachmen=\r\nt and equanimity in his advice to Arjuna, rather than trying to find out ca=\r\nuse-effect relationships of the apparently good or the apparently bad kinds=\r\n. \n\nSufferings are a great way of focusing on God. Really. Slowly but surel=\r\ny you realize that the world will run in its own pattern and you cannot do =\r\nmuch about it, except control what is in your power to control, that is you=\r\nr internal state. \n\nKrishna gives this advice to Arjuna in the Second Chapt=\r\ner: &quot;Dukhesva Anudhvigna-manah Sukhesu-Vigatasprhah Vita-Raga-Bhaya-Krodhah=\r\n Sthita-Dhira Munir Uchyate&quot; Gita 2:56 [Miseries do not agitate the mind, i=\r\nn sukha (fleeting happiness) there is no elation, such a one who is free fr=\r\nom attachment, fear and anger, is a sage of steady mind.]\n\nTough? Sure. But=\r\n no harm in making an effort. This is something to be tried on a regular ba=\r\nsis, day in and day out.\n\n&lt;&lt;2. Persons who do nothing =C3=82 in the field o=\r\nf spirituality can also meet God, higher saints. How is it possible?&gt;&gt;\n\nDep=\r\nends on what we understand by the term spirituality. Many have this notion =\r\nthat spirituality only means sitting and doing tough penances ETC. There is=\r\n more to spirituality than that. Essentially, it is a transformation of min=\r\nd, emotions and body (this bit is nearly impossible) into another state. \n\n=\r\nSadhana is needed to prepare the ground - mind/emotions/body. But *meeting =\r\nGod* (as you put it) depends on what you mean by God, and on God&#39;s sweet wi=\r\nll. Sometimes, living your daily life with an internal sense of surrender t=\r\no a Supreme, trying to inculcate equanimity in testing circumstances, tryin=\r\ng to stop the mind from automatically reacting to provocations, seeing othe=\r\nr people&#39;s point of views and thus becoming more objective, trying to be co=\r\nmpassionate (but not self-pity or pity in any form, for pity is a degenerat=\r\nive emotion, while compassion is uplifting) ETC are all sadhanas which can =\r\nbe done by anybody. One need not read complex scriptures, or believe in rel=\r\nigion to be able to do these. \n\n&lt;&lt;1. After effect of Homam can be negative =\r\nalso. Is it true?&gt;&gt;\n\nAfter effect of any sadhana can be negative (or positi=\r\nve), if your aim is anything materialistic. If your aim is purely spiritual=\r\n transformation, both so called negative and so called positive will help y=\r\nou. \n\n&lt;&lt;Fulfilling the duties of husband is a blockage in the spiritual pat=\r\nh.&gt;&gt;\n\nDharma is never a blockage. When the time is ripe, the Lord sets the =\r\npath. \n\nWhen Lord Krishna send Uddhava - who was a gyani of the first order=\r\n - to the Gopis, he was amazed to see that the Gopis would spend the whole =\r\nday doing whatever they must do, but they would perform every action, even =\r\nthe most mundane like clearing the garbage, with a small prayer in their li=\r\nps, &quot;Sri KrishNaaya Samarpayami..&quot;. \n\nPatience and surrender to God can be =\r\ninculcated, progressively, in any life situation. Infact, it is the ONLY th=\r\ning that you can work on. Rest, the world around apart from you, will follo=\r\nw its own rhythm which has been decided by actions performed in the past wh=\r\nich one may or maynot be aware of. \n\nEvery blockage is an opportunity to in=\r\ncrease the sense of surrender to something Higher, and that in turn acts as=\r\n a powerful internal catalyst for change.\n\nCaveat: These answers are based =\r\non my current perspective of things. They may not be sacrosanct. In future,=\r\n I myself may or may-not agree to these answers -:)\n\n-Regards\nRajarshi\n--- =\r\nIn vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com, gaurav tripathi &lt;gaurav_alld@...&gt; wrote:\n&gt;=\r\n\n&gt; Dear All Learned members,\n&gt; =C3=82=C2=A0 =C3=82=C2=A0Following are my qu=\r\nestions:\n&gt; 1. After effect of Homam can be negative also. Is it true?\n&gt; 2. =\r\nPersons who do nothing =C3=82=C2=A0in the field of spirituality can also me=\r\net God, higher saints. How is it possible?\n&gt; 3. I was reading =C3=82=C2=A0a=\r\n newspaper that people after having darshan of Mata Vaishno Devi, Kedarnaat=\r\nh, etc =C3=82=C2=A0, while returning, met with accident and died. Why does =\r\nthis happen? People have just come from a such a wonderful darshan then why=\r\n tragedy strikes them.\n&gt; 4. People who are married and have the wife and ki=\r\nd as responsibilities. Fulfilling the duties of husband is a blockage in th=\r\ne spiritual path. You know =C3=82=C2=A0what i mean.=C3=82=C2=A0\n&gt; 5. Why =\r\n=C3=82=C2=A0did Gautam Buddha left his wife and his child and even then ach=\r\nieved the status of God?\n&gt; 6. A common person gives =C3=82=C2=A0a damn to t=\r\nhe concept of liberation. When ever i =C3=82=C2=A0have discussion with peop=\r\nle in my office they think =C3=82=C2=A0i am mad . How should one deal with =\r\nthat because i =C3=82=C2=A0think that people =C3=82=C2=A0who are unaware of=\r\n this great concept should be taught with this id